# Wrapper Class in Java

# What is Wrapper Class?

Wrapper classes in Java are used to convert primitive data types into objects.

Java provides wrapper classes for all primitive data types.

## Definition

A wrapper class wraps (encloses) a primitive data type into an object.

---

# Why Wrapper Classes are Needed

Wrapper classes are useful because:

- Collections work only with objects
- Required for synchronization
- Helps in object conversion
- Used in Java utilities and frameworks
- Supports null values

---

# Primitive Data Types and Wrapper Classes

| Primitive Type | Wrapper Class |
|---|---|
| byte | Byte |
| short | Short |
| int | Integer |
| long | Long |
| float | Float |
| double | Double |
| char | Character |
| boolean | Boolean |

---

# Example of Wrapper Class

```java
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int num = 10;

        Integer obj = Integer.valueOf(num);

        System.out.println(obj);
    }
}
```

## Output

```java
10
```

---

# Types of Conversion

There are mainly two types of conversions:

1. Autoboxing
2. Unboxing

---

# 1. Autoboxing

## Definition

Automatic conversion of primitive type into wrapper object.

## Example

```java
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int a = 100;

        Integer obj = a;

        System.out.println(obj);
    }
}
```

## Output

```java
100
```

---

# 2. Unboxing

## Definition

Automatic conversion of wrapper object into primitive type.

## Example

```java
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Integer obj = 200;

        int num = obj;

        System.out.println(num);
    }
}
```

## Output

```java
200
```

